Sexual & Reproductive Health

{/* Common Concerns & FAQs Section */}

Common Concerns & FAQs

Reproductive Health

What is the normal menstrual cycle length?

A typical menstrual cycle can range from 21 to 35 days, with 28 days being average. However, cycle lengths can vary, and what's "normal" differs for each person.

When should I see a gynecologist?

Regular check-ups are recommended annually. However, consult immediately if you experience irregular bleeding, severe pain, or unusual discharge.

{/* Contraceptive Tools Section */}

Contraceptive Tools Guide

Barrier Methods

  • Male Condoms

    • Most commonly used barrier method
    • Protects against STIs
    • 98% effective when used correctly

  • Female Condoms

    • Can be inserted up to 8 hours before intercourse
    • Provides STI protection
    • 95% effective when used correctly

Hormonal Methods

  • Birth Control Pills

    • 99% effective when used correctly
    • Helps regulate menstrual cycles
    • May reduce menstrual cramps
{/* Fertility & Pregnancy Planning Section */}

Fertility & Pregnancy Planning

Understanding Fertility

  • Track your menstrual cycle
  • Monitor ovulation signs
  • Maintain a healthy lifestyle
  • Consider preconception vitamins

Best Time to Conceive

  • Identify your fertile window
  • Track basal body temperature
  • Monitor cervical mucus changes
  • Use ovulation prediction kits
{/* STI/STD Awareness Section */}

STI/STD Awareness

Understanding STIs vs STDs

An STI (Sexually Transmitted Infection) refers to the presence of an infection, while an STD (Sexually Transmitted Disease) occurs when the infection causes symptoms and disease. Not all STIs develop into STDs.

HPV & Cervical Cancer Prevention

  • Regular Pap smears
  • HPV vaccination
  • Safe sex practices
  • Regular check-ups

Prevention Tips

  • Practice safe sex
  • Get regular screenings
  • Know your partner's status
  • Communicate openly about sexual health
); }; export default SexualHealth;
